The paper deals with robot control problems and proposes a novel framework for dynamic movement primitives (DMPs) that can operate with symmetric positive definite (SPD) matrices. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of Riemannian metrics, which are commonly used in machine learning and optimization, indicating that the paper could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of manipulability ellipsoids, which are commonly used in computer vision and image processing, suggesting that the paper could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also deals with control theory and proposes a new formulation for DMPs, indicating that the paper could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of mathematical principles and proposes a new framework for DMPs, suggesting that the paper could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
